notesStmt.note: Title for first work from heading (f. 1r).
Incipit: Cy comance Les lamentacions Saint Bernard.

Title and attribution for second work from rubric following prologue: Cy aupres se sensuit la destruction de Troye translatee de latin en francoys mise par personnaiges par Maistre Jacques Millet estudiant en loys à Orleans l'an mil cccc et l" (f. 13v).

Title for third work from f. 449v; incipit: [A] la louenge Dieu de la Vierge souveraine de tous sains et de toutes sainctes et a la request de tres excellante et redoubte dame et puissant princesse dame Ysabel de Baviere reyne de France j'ai translate ceste Passion ... l'an de grace mil troys cens quatre vingtz et dishuit ... (f. 450r).
Date of composition of third work is 1398. La destruction de Troye, the second work, was composed 1450-1453, with the date of 1450 given at the end of the prologue (f. 13v).

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Collection of 3 separate works: Les lamentacions Saint Bernard [misattributed to St. Bernard of Clairvaux] (f. 1r-8v); La destruction de Troye by Jacques de Milet [in verse] (f. 9r-449r); and Le mystère de la Passion de Notre Sauveur Jesus Christ, translated from Latin in 1398 for Isabel of Bavaria, queen of France (f. 449v-487r).

msItem.title: Le myste?re de la Passion de Notre Sauveur Jesus Christ, f. 449v

supportDesc.extent: 487 leaves : 297 x 207 (215 x 140) mm. bound to 310 x 213 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, i (modern paper) + 487 + i (modern paper); [1-487]; modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 34 long lines; ruled in drypoint.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a Gothic cursive script by a single hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: Red used for some initials, with occasional decorations of faces and flourishes; capitals touched with yellow.

binding.p: Modern half leather over original boards, both covers detached.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Robert Churchill (inscription, flyleaf i recto).
Appears in Maggs Bros. catalog 816 (1954), no. 151.
